## What the score measures

Each company is scored across nine factors.

| Factor | Weight | What it measures |
|---|---:|---|
| Biology / target validation | 15% | Whether the underlying science, mechanism, and disease biology are credible |
| Clinical data quality | 20% | Strength, reproducibility, and relevance of available clinical or human data |
| Catalyst quality | 15% | Whether the next event could materially change valuation |
| Regulatory path | 10% | Clarity and plausibility of the FDA/EMA approval pathway |
| Commercial opportunity | 10% | Market size, unmet need, pricing potential, and adoption |
| Competitive differentiation | 10% | Whether the asset is meaningfully differentiated versus competitors |
| Cash runway / dilution risk | 10% | Whether the company is funded through key catalysts or may need financing |
| Management / BD validation | 5% | Quality of leadership, execution, partnerships, or pharma validation |
| Valuation asymmetry | 5% | Whether upside appears attractive relative to downside risk |

Each factor is scored from 0 to 5.

The weighted score is converted into a score out of 100.

---

## Rating system

| Score | Rating | Meaning |
|---:|---|---|
| 80+ | A — High-conviction watchlist | Strong investment case with credible data and meaningful catalysts |
| 70–79 | B — Catalyst watch | Attractive setup, but some risks still need monitoring |
| 60–69 | C — Speculative / volatile option | Interesting upside, but high uncertainty |
| 45–59 | D — Avoid unless thesis improves | Not compelling yet; needs stronger evidence or better valuation |
| <45 | E — Avoid | Weak or unattractive investment case |

